lus intensity","Follows all-or-none principle","Regenerates along the axon","Cannot undergo summation","Propagates without decrement"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Eamplitude varies with stimulus intensity\u003C/strong\u003E. Graded potentials are local electrical responses whose magnitude is proportional to the strength of the triggering stimulus. This is a fundamental characteristic that distinguishes them from action potentials.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropagates without decrement\u003C/strong\u003E - Graded potentials decrease in amplitude as they spread passively along the membrane\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollows all-or-none principle\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a characteristic of action potentials, not graded potentials\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECannot undergo summation\u003C/strong\u003E - Graded potentials can sum both temporally and spatially\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegenerates along the axon\u003C/strong\u003E - Only action potentials are regenerated; graded potentials conduct passively\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EGraded potentials are important for integrating multiple inputs at the trigger zone, where they may summate to reach threshold and generate an action potential if sufficient in magnitude.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Graded potentials vary in amplitude based on stimulus intensity and show decremental conduction.","Graded potentials can summate both temporally and spatially."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyt